    </figure>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Finding Slope by Two Given Points</title>
    <p>
      Several times in this section we computed a slope by drawing a slope triangle.
      That's not really necessary if you have coordinates for two points that a line passes through.
      In fact, sometimes it's impractical to draw a slope triangle.<fn>
      For instance if you only have specific information about two points that are too close together to draw a triangle,
      or if you cannot clearly see precise coordinates where you might start and stop your slope triangle.
      </fn> Here we will stress how to find a line's slope without drawing a slope triangle.
    </p>

    <example>
      <p>
        Your neighbor planted a sapling from a local nursery
        in his front yard.
        Ever since, for several years now,
        it has been growing at a constant rate.
        By the end of the third year, the tree was
        <quantity>
          <mag>15</mag><unit base="foot" />
        </quantity>
        tall; by the end of the sixth year, the tree was
        <quantity>
          <mag>27</mag><unit base="foot" />
        </quantity>
        tall.
        What's the tree's rate of growth (<ie/><nbsp/>the slope)?
      </p>

      <p>
        We <em>could</em> sketch a graph for this scenario,
        and include a slope triangle.
        If we did that, it would look like:
      </p>

      <sidebyside widths="44% 50%" margins="0%">
        <figure>
          <caption>Height of a Tree</caption>
          <image>
            <description>This is a grid with a line, passing the points (3,15) and (6,27). A slope triangle is drawn, starting at (3,15), passing (6,15), and ends at (6,27). The label from (3,15) to (6,15) is "6-3=3 years"; the label from (6,15) to (6,27) is "27-15=12 feet".</description>

            <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[xlabel={years since planting},
                            ylabel={height (ft)},
                            xmin=-1,xmax=9,
                            ymin=-3,ymax=30,
                            minor ytick=,
                            minor xtick=,
                            xtick={0,1,...,8},
                            ytick={0,3,...,27},
                            clip=false]
                    \addplot+[domain = 1:6.5]{4*x+3};
                      \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3, 15)} node[above left] {$(3,15)$};
                      \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(6, 27)} node[above left] {$(6,27)$};
                      \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(3,15) (6,15)} node[pos=0.5,below] {$3$ years};
                      \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(6,15) (6,27)} node[pos=0.5,below,rotate=90] {$12$ ft};
                \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
            </latex-image>
          </image>

        </figure>

        <p>
          By the slope triangle and <xref ref="equation-slope-definition">Equation</xref> we have:
          <md>
            <mrow>\text{slope}=m\amp =\frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp =\frac{12\,\text{ft}}{3\,\text{yr}}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp =4\frac{\text{ft}}{\text{yr}}</mrow>
          </md>
          So the tree is growing at a rate of
          <quantity>
            <mag>4</mag><unit base="foot" /><per base="year" />
          </quantity>.
        </p>
      </sidebyside>

      <p>
        But hold on.
        Did we really <em>need</em> this picture?
        The <q>rise</q> of <m>12</m> came from a subtraction of two <m>y</m>-values:
        <m>27-15</m>.
        And the <q>run</q> of <m>3</m> came from a subtraction of two <m>x</m>-values:
        <m>6-3</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        Here is a picture-free approach.
        We know that after
        <quantity>
          <mag>3</mag><unit base="year" />
        </quantity>, the height is
        <quantity>
          <mag>15</mag><unit base="foot" />
        </quantity>.
        As an ordered pair,
        that information gives us the point <m>(3,15)</m> which we can label as <m>(\overset{x_1}{3},\overset{y_1}{15})</m>.
        Similarly, the background information tells us to consider <m>(6,27)</m>,
        which we label as <m>(\overset{x_2}{6},\overset{y_2}{27})</m>.
        Here, <m>x_1</m> and <m>y_1</m> represent the first point's <m>x</m>-value and <m>y</m>-value,
        and <m>x_2</m> and <m>y_2</m> represent the second point's <m>x</m>-value and <m>y</m>-value.
      </p>
      <p>
        Now we can write an alternative to <xref ref="equation-slope-definition">Equation</xref>:
        <men xml:id="equation-slope-formula">
          \text{slope}=m=\frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}=\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}
        </men>
        This is known as the <term>slope formula</term>.
            <idx><h>slope</h><h>formula</h></idx>
        The following graphs help to understand why this formula works.
        Basically, we are still using a slope triangle to calculate the slope.
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="figure-slope-formula">
        <caption>Understanding the slope formula</caption>
        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%">

          <image>
            <description>This is a grid with a line, passing the points (3,15) and (6,27). A slope triangle is drawn, starting at (3,15), passing (6,15), and ends at (6,27). The label from (3,15) to (6,15) is "6-3=3 years"; the label from (6,15) to (6,27) is "27-15=12 feet".</description>

            <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[xlabel={years since planting},
                            ylabel={height (ft)},
                            xmin=-1,xmax=9,
                            ymin=-3,ymax=30,
                            minor ytick=,
                            minor xtick=,
                            xtick={},
                            ytick={},
                            clip=false]
                    \addplot+[domain = 1:6.5]{4*x+3};
                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3, 15)} node[above left] {$(3,15)$};
                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(6, 27)} node[above left] {$(6,27)$};
                    \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(3,15) (6,15)} node[pos=0.5,below,align=left] {$6-3$\\${}=3$ years};
                    \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(6,15) (6,27)} node[pos=0.5,below,rotate=90,align=left] {$27-15$\\${}=12$ ft};
                \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
            </latex-image>
          </image>

          <image>
            <description>This is a grid with a line, passing the points (3,15) and (6,27). A slope triangle is drawn, starting at (3,15), passing (6,15), and ends at (6,27). The label from (3,15) to (6,15) is "x2-x1"; the label from (6,15) to (6,27) is "y2-y1".</description>

            <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[xmin=-1,xmax=9,
                            ymin=-3,ymax=30,
                            minor ytick=,
                            minor xtick=,
                            xtick={},
                            ytick={},
                            clip=false]
                    \addplot+[domain = 1:6.5]{4*x+3};
                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3, 15)} node[above left] {$(x_1,y_1)$};
                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(6, 27)} node[above left] {$(x_2,y_2)$};
                    \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(3,15) (6,15)} node[pos=0.5,below,align=left] {$x_2-x_1$};
                    \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(6,15) (6,27)} node[pos=0.5,below,rotate=90,align=left] {$y_2-y_1$};
                \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
            </latex-image>
          </image>

        </sidebyside>

      </figure>
    </example>

    <remark>
      <p>
        It's important to use subscript instead of superscript in the slope equation,
        because <m>y^2</m> means to take the number <m>y</m> and square it.
        Whereas <m>y_2</m> tells you that there are at least two <m>y</m>-values in the conversation,
        and <m>y_2</m> is the second of them.
      </p>
    </remark>

    <p>
      The beauty of the <xref ref="equation-slope-formula" text="custom">slope formula</xref>
      is that to find a line's slope,
      we don't need to draw a slope triangle any more.
      Let's look at an example.
    </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A line passes the points <m>(-5,25)</m> and
          <m>(4,-2)</m>. Find this line's slope.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          If you are new to this formula,
          it may help to label each number before using the formula.
          The two given points are:
          <me>
            (\overset{x_1}{-5},\overset{y_1}{25}) \text{ and } (\overset{x_2}{4},\overset{y_2}{-2})
          </me>
          Now apply the <xref ref="equation-slope-formula" text="custom">slope formula</xref>:
          <md>
            <mrow>\text{slope}\amp=\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=\frac{-2-25}{4-(-5)}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=\frac{-27}{9}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=-3</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>
          Note that we used parentheses when substituting negative numbers in <m>x_1</m> and <m>y_1</m>.
          This is a good habit to protect yourself from making errors with subtraction and double negatives.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <exercise>
      <webwork source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/SlopeAndY-InterceptCalculations/SlopeFormula70.pg" />
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

